	<div style="padding: 4px;"><span class="postbody"><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="2" border="0" align="center" class="quote"><tr> 	<td class="quote_user">Isriam wrote:</td></tr><tr>	<td class="quote">This isn't everquest 1.  Heals stack.  I don't care if there's 5 healers spamming.  You created macro's in EQ1 because heals didn't stack and once a tank was healed you couldn't heal him any farther which was wasting mana.  You also had complete heal.  You have none of that here, every heal buff on a tank is fine.  Especially if he's getting hit 4-5 times a round for 300+.</td>	</tr></table>
<br />

<br />

<br />
Yeppers... I don't have any macros at this point, and honestly....I don't need them.
<br />

<br />
Most of the tanks I group with have an incoming, and that is all.
<br />

<br />
Most people could care less if I am casting a heal or not...As long as the tank stays alive....The only person worried about the tanks health is me and the tank. No one else in the group could care less.
<br />

<br />
In a group with two clerics.....You had better figure out who's heals you are going to use. At that point, a battle cleric isn't bad. A battle cleric can debuff, heal, buff, and dps. Hmm.....Sounds a lot like a Templar doesn't it? I never group with two clerics... I learned that lesson. Our heals stack with Wardens and Mystics, but not with Templars. At that point, you get into the whole my BoV is App3 versus Adept 1...Too messy, imo. If I get into that situation, I get out of it very quickly.
<br />

<br />
Communication is a good thing. But, too much is worthless. A tank pulls with one incoming message, even if they pull 4 mobs. They just add an extra line in with the number.
<br />

<br />
Will I use macros during raids...YES!!!!!!!!!!! That's when it is useful, not in a group setting.
<br />

<br />
This is EQ2, not EQL.</span></div>
	</td>
</tr>
